<h2>Overview — why this partner is uniquely valuable</h2>
<p>Most of the <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> depends on <em>interpreting</em> climate science honestly. The Climate Modeler is tuned for two specific moves: (1) reading IPCC AR6 figures correctly, including the confidence-level language ("likely" / "very likely" / "virtually certain") that has specific probability meanings; and (2) holding the distinction between <strong>projection</strong> (what models say <em>under specific scenario assumptions</em>) and <strong>prediction</strong> (what will happen — which climate models don't do).</p>
<p>It's also tuned for climate-anxiety students. Climate content is heavy. The partner can hold scientific honesty + emotional acknowledgement at the same time — it neither catastrophises nor dismisses, and it'll push back if you slip into either denial or hopelessness.</p>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">The Source Evaluator</a></strong> — when you're applying OPVL to specific IPCC + government + AI sources. The Source Evaluator walks the four letters; the Climate Modeler helps you interpret what the source actually says before you OPVL it.</p>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/policy-aide/">The Policy Aide</a></strong> — different roles, complementary. The Climate Modeler handles science interpretation; the Policy Aide handles policy translation. If you ask the Climate Modeler "should GCC fund this?" it'll redirect you to the Policy Aide.</p>

